1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:09,075
(John 4:23): 'Madam, the hour is coming and now is, when the true worshipers will worship the Father in spirit and truth.

2
00:00:09,025 --> 00:00:11,612
This comes from St John’s Gospel.

3
00:00:11,612 --> 00:00:14,575
I take one sentence from a long discourse.

4
00:00:14,575 --> 00:00:23,425
Our Lord said: ‘Woman, the hour cometh and now is, when true worshippers shall worship the Father in spirit and in truth and the Father seeketh such.

5
00:00:23,425 --> 00:00:27,400
Taking the opening words: ‘The hour cometh and now is.

6
00:00:27,400 --> 00:00:33,125
He who would worship the Father must betake himself into eternity in his desires and hopes.

7
00:00:33,125 --> 00:00:39,637
There is one, the loftiest, part of the soul which stands above time and knows nothing of time or of body.

8
00:00:39,637 --> 00:00:54,725
The happenings of a thousand years ago, days spent millenniums since, are in eternity no further off than is this moment I am passing now; the day to come a thousand years ahead or in as many years as you can count, is no more distant in eternity than this very instant I am in.

9
00:00:54,725 --> 00:00:59,500
He says, ‘true worshippers worship the Father in spirit and in truth.

10
00:00:59,500 --> 00:01:00,875
What is truth?

11
00:01:00,875 --> 00:01:03,287
The truth is a most noble thing.

12
00:01:03,287 --> 00:01:08,550
If God were able to backslide from truth I would fain cling to truth and let God go.

13
00:01:08,550 --> 00:01:14,012
But God is truth, and things in time, the things that God created, are not truth.

14
00:01:14,012 --> 00:01:16,550
He says, ‘they worship the Father.

15
00:01:16,550 --> 00:01:22,050
Alas, how many worship creatures and saddle themselves with them, fools that they are.

16
00:01:22,050 --> 00:01:31,537
As sure as thou dost pray to God for creatures thou prayest for thine own undoing, for no sooner is creature creature than hey for trouble and bitterness, wrong and distress.

17
00:01:31,537 --> 00:01:36,225
They get their deserts, do these folk, with their wrongs and their bitterness.

18
00:01:36,225 --> 00:01:37,312
For why?

19
00:01:37,312 --> 00:01:38,912
They prayed for it.

20
00:01:38,912 --> 00:01:50,575
I have sometimes said, whoso goes seeking God and seeking aught with God does not find God; but he who seeks God by himself in truth does not find God alone: all God affords he finds as well as God.

21
00:01:50,575 --> 00:01:56,625
Art thou looking for God, seeking God with a view to thy personal good, thy personal profit?

22
00:01:56,625 --> 00:01:59,412
Then in truth thou art not seeking God.

23
00:01:59,412 --> 00:02:04,100
True worshippers worship the Father,’ he says, and he says right well.

24
00:02:04,100 --> 00:02:09,937
If a virtuous man is asked, ‘Why dost thou seek God?’ he answers: ‘Because he is God.

25
00:02:09,937 --> 00:02:11,950
Why dost thou seek truth?

26
00:02:11,950 --> 00:02:13,637
Because it is truth.

27
00:02:13,637 --> 00:02:15,550
Why dost thou seek right?

28
00:02:15,550 --> 00:02:18,650
Because it is right,’ and with such all is well.

29
00:02:18,650 --> 00:02:21,437
Things here in time have each their cause.

30
00:02:21,437 --> 00:02:23,462
Ask a man why he eats?

31
00:02:23,462 --> 00:02:25,462
For strength,’ he says.

32
00:02:25,462 --> 00:02:26,962
Why he sleeps?

33
00:02:26,962 --> 00:02:28,887
For the very same reason.

34
00:02:28,887 --> 00:02:31,100
And so with everything in time.

35
00:02:31,100 --> 00:02:34,312
But ask a good man, ‘Why dost thou love God?

36
00:02:34,312 --> 00:02:37,425
He says: ‘I know not; for God’s sake.

37
00:02:37,425 --> 00:02:39,500
Why dost thou love the truth?

38
00:02:39,500 --> 00:02:41,150
For the truth’s sake.

39
00:02:41,150 --> 00:02:43,075
Why dost thou love right?

40
00:02:43,075 --> 00:02:44,962
For righteousness’ sake.

41
00:02:44,962 --> 00:02:46,837
Why dost thou love good?

42
00:02:46,837 --> 00:02:48,250
For good’s sake.

43
00:02:48,250 --> 00:02:49,912
Why dost thou live?

44
00:02:49,912 --> 00:02:51,825
I’ faith, I know not!

45
00:02:51,825 --> 00:02:53,200
I like living.

46
00:02:53,200 --> 00:03:03,562
A philosopher says: ‘He who has once been touched by truth, by right, by good, though it entailed the pangs of hell, that man could never turn therefrom, not for an instant.

47
00:03:03,562 --> 00:03:12,162
The man, whoe’er he be, moved by these three—truth, righteousness and goodness—can no more quit these three than God can quit his Godhood.

48
00:03:12,162 --> 00:03:15,625
A philosopher says that goodness has three branches.

49
00:03:15,625 --> 00:03:20,325
The first is use, the second is enjoyment and the third is seemliness.

50
00:03:20,325 --> 00:03:23,662
Concerning his words, ‘they worship the Father.

51
00:03:23,662 --> 00:03:25,512
Why does he say ‘the Father’?

52
00:03:25,512 --> 00:03:29,625
Seek God alone and thou shalt find with God all that he gives.

53
00:03:29,625 --> 00:03:43,600
It is the positive truth, true of necessity, a written axiom though no less true unwritten, that if God had more he could not keep it from thee, he would have to show it thee, to give it thee, and, as I sometimes say, he gives it to thee as a birth.

54
00:03:43,756 --> 00:03:59,606
Philosophers say the soul is double-faced, her upper face gazes at God all the time and her lower face looks somewhat down, informing the senses; and the upper face, which is the summit of the soul, is in eternity and has nothing to do with time: it knows nothing of time or of body.

55
00:03:59,556 --> 00:04:10,968
Elsewhere I have explained how in this lies hid the fount as it were of all good, as a shining light that is always shining, a burning brand that is always burning, which brand is none other than the Holy Ghost.

56
00:04:10,968 --> 00:04:15,631
Philosophers say that out of the summit of the soul there flow twin powers.

57
00:04:15,631 --> 00:04:21,968
The one is will, the other intellect, and her powers’ perfection lies in the sovran power of intellect.

58
00:04:21,968 --> 00:04:23,631
This never rests.

59
00:04:23,631 --> 00:04:28,306
It wants God not as Holy Ghost nor yet as Son; it flees the Son.

60
00:04:28,306 --> 00:04:30,418
It wants God not as God.

61
00:04:30,418 --> 00:04:31,468
And why?

62
00:04:31,468 --> 00:04:42,006
Because thus he has name; were there a thousand Gods yet would it penetrate them all in the desire to get to where he has no name at all: it wants a nobler, better thing than God as having name.

63
00:04:42,006 --> 00:04:43,768
What would it, then?

64
00:04:43,768 --> 00:04:46,618
It does not know: it would have him Father.

65
00:04:46,618 --> 00:04:51,331
Lord, show us the Father,’ Philip cries, ‘and we shall be content.

66
00:04:51,331 --> 00:05:00,331
It wants him as the quick of kindness; it wants him as the marrow dripping fatness; it wants him as the root, the main of goodness: thus he is simply Father.

67
00:05:00,331 --> 00:05:05,731
Our Lord says: ‘No man knoweth the Father but the Son, nor the Son but the Father.

68
00:05:05,731 --> 00:05:09,218
In truth, to know the Father we must be the Son.

69
00:05:09,218 --> 00:05:14,456
I have laid down these three maxims which take like three bad grapes and drink thereafter.

70
00:05:14,456 --> 00:05:22,481
First, if we are Son, we must have the Father: none can say he is a son unless he has a father, nor father unless he has a son.

71
00:05:22,481 --> 00:05:25,793
His father dead, he says, ‘he was my father.

72
00:05:25,793 --> 00:05:29,206
His son being dead, he says, ‘he was my son.

73
00:05:29,206 --> 00:05:43,243
The son’s life hangs upon the father, and the father’s on the son, and therefore none can say: ‘I am the Son’ unless he have the Father and he is in truth Son whose every work is wrought for love therein.—Secondly, that which most makes man Son is equability.

74
00:05:43,243 --> 00:05:47,281
Being sick he would as soon be sick as sane, as sane as sick.

75
00:05:47,281 --> 00:05:49,806
His friend dies, ‘In God’s name!

76
00:05:49,806 --> 00:05:52,281
He has an eye out, ‘In God’s name!

77
00:05:52,281 --> 00:05:56,881
Thirdly, it beseems the Son to bow the head to no one save the Father.

78
00:05:56,881 --> 00:06:01,568
Truly, a royal power this, transcending time and without place!

79
00:06:01,568 --> 00:06:14,906
And by the fact of its transcending time it both contains all time and is the whole of time, and the least jot of that which transcends time makes a man rich indeed, for things at the antipodes are no more distant to this power than those present here.

80
00:06:14,906 --> 00:06:18,418
It is of these he says, ‘the Father seeketh such.

81
00:06:18,418 --> 00:06:32,481
Look you, God loves us so, God importunes us so, because God cannot work till the soul is shelled and trimmed of creatures, and the plain truth is that of necessity God is bound to cherish us just as though his Godhood were at stake, as in fact it is.

82
00:06:32,481 --> 00:06:40,668
God can no more do without us than we can without him, nay, even if we turned from God it would be impossible for God to turn his back on us.

83
00:06:40,668 --> 00:06:51,881
I vow I will not pray to God for gifts nor worship him because of gifts bestowed, but I will entreat him to make me worthy to receive and worship him for being of the essence and of the nature that must give.

84
00:06:51,881 --> 00:06:57,006
He who would spoil God of this would spoil him of his very life, of his very being.

85
00:06:57,006 --> 00:07:01,656
That we may thus in truth be Son, help us the truth of which I speak.

86
00:07:01,656 --> 00:07:02,606
Amen.
